  <title translate="true">YaxisUnitsatStart</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword translate="true">Y-Axis:<keyword translate="true">Units at Start</keyword></keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para><table styleclass="MotionPupup" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">The word &apos;</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="text-decoration:underline;" translate="true">units&apos;</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> is replaced in the dialog-box by the actual &apos;unit&apos; being used for the Y–axis. The Default Value for the &apos;Y–axis Units at Start&apos; value will be zero. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true">Frequently a motion that is being designed for a machine element will be most easily designed without considering any offset. The position is designed </text><text styleclass="Popup Box" style="text-decoration:underline;" translate="true">relative</text><text styleclass="Popup Box" translate="true"> to an initial position. However, the motion can be saved with an offset so that an absolute can be given. Note, the offset can be applied using the Base Value of the Motion-Dimension Function-Block in </text><text styleclass="VariableName-IT" style="font-size:10pt;" translate="true">MechDesigner</text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
